17:15.860 --> 17:19.980
Now that I'm finally broken in, I'll have a better chance at selling something over.

17:21.840 --> 17:29.540
Is it true that when he lived in cross planes, you know, the last, what, what, 10 years? How long was he in cross planes?

17:29.740 --> 17:31.560
I lived in cross planes when he, in his junior high.

17:31.760 --> 17:41.300
Oh, okay, that long. Okay. Well, when he was earning his money as a writer, say at the, oh, year two before his death, was he making, I read a statement, more money than anybody in cross planes?

17:41.480 --> 17:42.580
That's what Jack Scott says.

17:42.900 --> 17:43.520
You think that's true?

17:45.600 --> 17:47.760
For depression. Now this is depression days course.

17:48.120 --> 17:57.720
The story in Brownwood is that he was the only man either in Brown County or maybe just in cross planes who could afford to buy a new car and pay cash for it.

17:57.760 --> 18:00.160
And he was the only one who paid income tax one year.

18:00.600 --> 18:02.720
It was only one in cross planes who had to pay income tax.

18:02.860 --> 18:05.420
And when he died, he did have a car that was only one year old.

18:05.960 --> 18:10.880
It was a Chevrolet that was a year old and maybe not even quite a year.

18:10.880 --> 18:18.860
And he had paid cash for it and he did leave some money in the bank and he had a paid up insurance policy made out to his mother.

18:19.020 --> 18:20.720
She survived it by 11 days.

18:20.940 --> 18:28.540
So his father had to go through this legal rigmarole since his wife didn't leave a will so that he could collect this insurance policy.

18:29.420 --> 18:31.000
Was he helping to support his mother?

18:31.460 --> 18:32.460
Was there any kind of?

18:32.940 --> 18:35.840
Oh, I feel certain that, that he did.

18:35.840 --> 18:37.820
And at least he said so in his letters now again.

18:38.200 --> 18:40.760
Maybe he wanted to feel that he was necessary to his parents.

18:41.300 --> 18:48.740
His father was making enough money that he mentioned in his letters that the cost of medicine was so expensive and the things that they needed was very expensive.

18:50.800 --> 18:56.140
I'm kind of interested also in Howard's consciousness of himself as a writer.

18:59.000 --> 19:11.840
Did he think that he, in your opinions, of course, do you think that he thought of himself as a writer who would be remembered as anything more than a person simply making a living as an author?

19:11.920 --> 19:18.920
Didn't he have a consciousness of himself as possibly being remembered as a regional writer of the Southwest for some of his Western material?

19:18.920 --> 19:27.420
Or, I mean, you know, just his own attitude about himself as a creator, as an author who would be remembered.

19:28.560 --> 19:29.800
Any ideas about that?

19:30.460 --> 19:38.160
As far as I know, the only thing that I've even heard would be about the regional, the Southwestern material, some of the Western stories.

19:38.720 --> 19:46.460
I don't know that he ever thought that these other stories were that literary or maybe even that important.

19:46.460 --> 19:56.440
You know, he cannibalized some stories that he would write, set in one time frame, he would go back and rewrite them using other characters.

19:56.860 --> 19:59.260
Not that that would make any difference, I don't guess.

19:59.660 --> 20:05.060
But I think he did have a desire to be remembered. He wanted to be a great artist.

20:05.460 --> 20:08.600
And I think that's why he decided to do an epic of Southwest.

20:08.600 --> 20:27.060
That's what he told Lovecraft, he wanted to do. He wanted to do an epic of Texas and the Southwest and he wrote this long genealogical thing saying he had a feel for it because his people had been here and his grandfathers had been in the Confederacy and all this, that and the other of why he had this strong feeling for it.

20:27.320 --> 20:34.840
But I think he was looking for something. As you said, he knew that the stories he was writing at the time probably would not be remembered immortally.

20:34.840 --> 20:38.420
He would be quite surprised, I think, to find out Conan's popularity today.

20:39.020 --> 20:45.780
But he had a desire to be remembered and he was looking for a medium in which he would excel.

20:46.640 --> 20:57.380
I think it was Lovecraft, I know for Lovecraft for sure, but I think some others too who said that had he lived and had he continued to write that he would have written more regional, more Western stories, perhaps the epic of the Southwest.

20:58.640 --> 20:59.840
That's what DeKant thinks.

20:59.840 --> 21:02.980
Yeah, and DeKant thinks the same thing, that he would be remembered for that.

21:05.180 --> 21:11.960
Did he do any work in that direction beyond his Breckenridge, Pike Bearfield?

21:13.360 --> 21:21.960
Yeah, okay. Beyond the work that he had published in the field of the West, are there any notes that you know of or any kind of attempt to start an epic of the region?

21:21.960 --> 21:31.120
Not a start for epic, no. There were some fragments of other Western tales found in those two trolls and manuscripts that DeKant dug up.

21:34.720 --> 21:41.640
Dr. Kreider, we may have to cut this. I'm not sure I'm going the right direction here.

21:41.960 --> 21:42.500
Don't worry about it.

21:43.200 --> 21:44.820
Have you read any of his Western work?

21:45.540 --> 21:46.700
Only a few stories.

21:48.380 --> 21:51.960
I've heard DeKant read one that he thinks very highly of. I forgot.

21:52.120 --> 21:53.300
About shooting off the air.

21:53.500 --> 21:53.820
Right.

21:54.200 --> 21:58.280
Well, what I wanted to ask about that, I've read most of his Western work myself.

22:00.280 --> 22:06.380
People have said he had a feeling for the idiom of the West, the regionalisms, the atmosphere and so forth.

22:07.580 --> 22:09.320
But it was still, what I've read is still the pulp.

22:10.840 --> 22:15.520
What? The pulp environment, the pulp formulas for the stories.

22:15.520 --> 22:26.080
Do you think he, did he have his roots deeply enough or a feeling for the West deeply enough where he could have written a realistic kind of Western material?

22:26.500 --> 22:27.980
Could he have become the Louis Lemur?

22:28.500 --> 22:32.020
No, no, I mean more seriously. I mean a good but great literature.

22:32.260 --> 22:38.220
Did he have the talent or was he so imbued with the pulp environment that...

22:38.220 --> 22:42.840
He may have had the talent, but I certainly don't believe he was capable of writing realistic fiction.

22:42.840 --> 22:46.480
He was not that closely tied to reality himself.

22:47.040 --> 22:51.700
I don't believe he ever could have written realistic novels. He had derived fantasies of some sort.

22:52.620 --> 22:57.080
He may have had the talent, but I don't think he had the personal realism to do it.

22:58.000 --> 23:01.260
His Western material, most of it that I've read is humorous.

23:01.800 --> 23:02.520
Probably right.

23:02.620 --> 23:04.500
Right. I think that's what DeKant admires.

23:04.520 --> 23:04.840
Yes.

23:04.960 --> 23:06.620
It's the humorous aspect of it.

23:06.620 --> 23:15.860
And he seems to think that that might have been the direction he was going more to the humorous Western than the realistic Western.

23:15.940 --> 23:21.920
Of course we have to say a little bit of DeKant in that conclusion because DeKant writes humorous science fiction.

23:22.560 --> 23:26.980
And you tend to think, well he would have become more like me.

23:27.580 --> 23:32.120
And in fact it's DeKant's life-heartedness that some people can't forgive him for.

23:32.120 --> 23:39.620
They accuse him of making Conan into a huckish character, which was not really in Howard's original audience.

23:40.080 --> 23:42.720
Conan certainly wasn't very huckish. He wasn't very funny.

23:43.100 --> 23:53.120
Well at the risk of outraging all the Howard fans, and Charlotte keeps saying maybe he had the talent,

23:53.120 --> 24:04.320
but where is that really in evidence in the stories that we have of Robert E. Howard as a great writer or a great stylist or,

24:05.440 --> 24:08.380
I'm not sure that there's any evidence of that.

24:08.500 --> 24:15.940
I think he was a fine pulp writer, and I don't have anything bad to say about his pulp work,

24:15.940 --> 24:27.660
but I don't know that he would ever have broken out of that pulp ghetto and be accepted by what we might call the approved literature standards.

24:28.740 --> 24:32.400
Since he was writing for Money Towards the End, he definitely was.

24:33.040 --> 24:39.340
It would be very hard to break out of the pulp syndrome that he was in because he was having to write what people wanted to read.

24:39.480 --> 24:43.920
Now I think parts of Conan are fairly literary, but then you'll get to a fairly good point,

24:43.920 --> 24:46.600
and then he'll have another one of those wrestling matches with a giant snake,

24:47.140 --> 24:51.560
the same formulas that he's used in a dozen other places, and they get very old and very trite.

24:51.880 --> 24:58.180
But there are a paragraph or two at a time where it sounds as though he really did have a command of the language that I like.

24:58.300 --> 24:59.480
I like the sound of it.

25:00.020 --> 25:07.460
And also though he was interested in history and studied art and art, there are a lot of inaccuracies.

25:07.460 --> 25:09.680
Go ahead and back that up. He was interested in history.

25:09.680 --> 25:14.340
Although he was interested in history and studied it and had a lot of books in his collection,

25:15.180 --> 25:24.780
he can't find a number of anachronisms in some of the Conan manuscripts and even changed one or two of them in some of those pastiches that he did.

25:25.160 --> 25:31.280
Yes, I believe one was the stirrups that you mentioned that had him in stirrups before there were stirrups.

25:31.820 --> 25:37.680
But since this is a completely imaginary world and how boy in age had a way, we know they didn't have stirrups.

25:37.680 --> 25:40.860
Yeah, but I wonder whether he would have been a...

25:40.860 --> 25:42.680
You know, he's not...

25:47.220 --> 25:49.960
No, okay. You needed to lead in on something.

25:50.520 --> 25:51.560
I wasn't going to change the subject.

25:52.200 --> 25:53.680
Okay, we were talking about...

25:54.620 --> 25:54.800
Stirrups.

25:54.940 --> 25:57.280
Well, that would fit right in doing research, blah, blah, blah.

25:57.540 --> 26:03.860
She just mentioned that he wore stirrups and that was out of context.

26:05.200 --> 26:06.860
And you were just saying...

26:07.920 --> 26:13.580
I was just saying that I don't know if he had ever written westerns other than the humorous kind,

26:14.000 --> 26:20.160
whether he would have had the stamina or whatever is required to do accurate historical research.

26:20.560 --> 26:25.400
And it might be that he would just have relied on old family stories and things like that.

26:25.780 --> 26:33.200
Yeah, a lot of the books that I noticed in the library here at Howard Payne were the Lowell Thomas History Series,

26:33.200 --> 26:36.940
which is somewhat colorful and not exactly accurate.

26:40.140 --> 26:46.560
And Dr. Laughlin has the list of his books that we have, and we can confirm that.

26:47.320 --> 26:51.700
He did have, I'm sure, some more solid kinds of historical research,

26:51.800 --> 26:56.360
but I don't think that's what his personal taste was inclined to.

26:56.380 --> 27:01.340
I think he would have relied not even so much on family stories as he would have on his own reading.

27:01.820 --> 27:04.420
And he read things like Robert Service novels.

27:04.540 --> 27:08.140
He had that said one, two, three, four, five, six of those.

27:08.360 --> 27:09.380
Sorry, I was counting.

27:09.660 --> 27:10.440
Okay, wait, wait, okay.

27:10.580 --> 27:11.740
Mic up and talk about the Robert...

27:11.740 --> 27:13.040
He had...

27:13.040 --> 27:18.320
I was saying that I thought that Robert Howard not only would have relied upon family stories,

27:18.340 --> 27:22.500
but even more so he would have relied upon his own reading of fiction.

27:22.900 --> 27:25.440
And his taste in fiction doesn't seem to be too high.

27:25.840 --> 27:28.120
He read things like the Robert Service novels.

27:28.120 --> 27:33.620
We know that there were six Robert Service books in his personal library that his father donated to Howard Paine.

27:33.840 --> 27:35.300
Micah, what were the Robert Service novels?

27:36.300 --> 27:38.640
Well, he wrote several different kinds.

27:38.780 --> 27:39.860
He wrote Robert Service poetry.

27:40.620 --> 27:43.520
And Robert Service wrote poetry, but it was...

27:43.520 --> 27:44.520
I won't...

27:44.520 --> 27:45.640
How would you describe it, Bill?

27:46.240 --> 27:47.020
I haven't read them.

27:47.520 --> 27:50.020
Well, I read this kind of thing when I was growing up.

27:50.180 --> 27:51.720
They're very melodramatic.

27:52.320 --> 27:54.760
His war stories were very melodramatic.

27:54.760 --> 27:58.360
And you have this lone hero and he's so noble and so good.

27:58.360 --> 28:01.580
But I would not say that Robert Service writing is really realistic.

28:01.960 --> 28:05.880
He had a lot of sax-roamer books in his collection.

28:05.900 --> 28:12.060
Also, the Oriental, Exotic, Romantic type of thing.

28:12.900 --> 28:17.780
I just can't picture Howard as a realistic writer in any way.

28:18.340 --> 28:20.760
Well, he had to get almost all of his...

28:20.760 --> 28:22.660
What do you want to call it? Inspiration for his fiction?

28:22.840 --> 28:25.760
Buy his reading from his reading because it's sort of an...

28:25.760 --> 28:34.240
Another of DeKamp's points is that that's a weakness in Howard's work is that he never traveled to see these things.

28:34.380 --> 28:37.080
He never really got out of cross planes.

28:37.460 --> 28:39.600
He did a little, but not much.

28:39.780 --> 28:44.720
In fact, some of the incidents in his novels you can find in other novels that he had read.

28:44.860 --> 28:47.100
And I'm sorry, I can't remember the specific examples.

28:47.100 --> 28:51.160
We do know that, I believe it was Simeron by Edna Farber.

28:51.520 --> 28:56.540
He told Lovecraft, he wrote Lovecraft, that this incident had really happened in cross planes.

28:56.760 --> 28:58.240
And it was an incident in Simeron.

29:01.580 --> 29:04.320
Well, Howard relied heavily on the reading that he did.

29:05.860 --> 29:06.380
Is that okay?

29:07.720 --> 29:11.000
He relied so heavily on it that in his letters he actually...

29:11.000 --> 29:12.200
No, wait a minute. Go ahead and start again.

29:12.700 --> 29:14.520
I have to have room to edit the clicks and stuff out.

29:15.420 --> 29:18.820
Howard relied heavily on the reading that he did.

29:19.380 --> 29:21.440
He relied on it for his fiction.

29:21.640 --> 29:25.240
Also, he claimed that some of the incidents actually happened in his own life.

29:25.640 --> 29:32.580
He wrote Lovecraft, that an incident in which something was blown up in an oil field.

29:33.180 --> 29:37.020
I can't remember exactly what it was, and that you had to be in great physical shape

29:37.020 --> 29:42.120
because this man was able to catch it in his arms and run with it to save the lives of all of these people.

29:42.120 --> 29:45.160
But the incident did not happen in cross planes.

29:45.320 --> 29:49.880
It happened in the novel Simeron, which was in his personal library, which was done in Tyler Penn.

29:50.660 --> 29:58.520
So he had such a slight grasp of the reality or such slight experience in the world

29:58.520 --> 30:03.180
that he actually had to claim things from novels to have been in his experience

30:03.180 --> 30:05.060
to have things to write about to people.

30:06.660 --> 30:11.420
Who are some of the other authors that he would have had in his library that he liked to read?

30:11.420 --> 30:13.640
So, you know, the writer, the creator's of fiction.

30:13.740 --> 30:16.340
I had about six Conan Doll books.

30:17.360 --> 30:25.040
I was wondering how much influence the Conan series and Brian McMoron and all the barbarian type series had

30:25.040 --> 30:29.960
from Egyrace Burrow's books that I noticed he had a few of those.

30:31.660 --> 30:33.840
Well, I'm really not qualified to tell you that.

30:34.020 --> 30:36.440
He had one that I say, the Beast of Tarzan.

30:38.020 --> 30:42.620
Well, Tarzan and Conan are similar enough.

30:43.400 --> 30:48.000
Outcasts. I mean, they don't actually fit in with the fun of the male type of person, I mean.

30:48.460 --> 30:49.960
Which is what Howard wanted to be.

30:50.400 --> 30:53.500
Away from civilization. Superman, sort of.

30:55.060 --> 30:58.480
Isn't it sort of strange? This is sort of a summation, I think, of what we've been saying.

30:59.340 --> 31:02.940
To have a writer of fantasy, particularly the kind that Howard wrote,

31:03.680 --> 31:07.240
which I associate mostly with the northern environment, I suppose.

31:07.960 --> 31:12.100
Coming from the Southwest, from such an arid landscape, from such a small town,

31:13.880 --> 31:20.320
you know, was so little traveling in his life, he would have had to have gotten everything from his imagination from books

31:21.600 --> 31:23.380
because he had not experienced any of that.

31:23.640 --> 31:25.140
To me, that's always been sort of a paradox.

31:26.100 --> 31:30.080
Part of it was, I think, his interest in the Celtic heritage.

31:31.220 --> 31:39.920
Wasn't that one of his big things, the belief in his famous or royal ancestors, which may or may not have existed,

31:40.300 --> 31:41.840
like Dr. Laugh, I'll tell you.

31:42.100 --> 31:47.800
He claimed that he was full blood Irish, and they were the Irish kings, like some other people we now claim to be.

31:48.280 --> 31:51.260
But there's no evidence that he certainly was not full blood Irish.

31:51.360 --> 31:56.240
People have traced his genealogy, but this was part of his image of himself.

31:56.240 --> 31:59.720
He was trying to project other people and trying to create for himself.

32:01.040 --> 32:10.160
There again, he wrote at one time that he wrote about the barren, cold, windswept, damp areas, even though he lived here.

32:10.440 --> 32:16.140
I think that again might be a sort of wishful film, and who wouldn't like to be someplace where it's cold on a day like this.

32:16.420 --> 32:22.760
He wanted to be away from where he was because I don't think we can underestimate the anger and frustration

32:23.180 --> 32:25.920
that was boiling around in Robert Howard all the time.

32:26.020 --> 32:32.880
I see it in all of his poetry, and a great deal of his fiction.

32:33.900 --> 32:40.720
Cross Plains neighbors say that he had a, there was a big tree stump out by his yard, and I believe it was a sledgehammer, not an axe.

32:41.140 --> 32:45.220
And sometimes in the middle of the day, he would go out there, you know, and he would just see that he was so tense,

32:45.640 --> 32:50.240
and he would take that sledgehammer and he would just wham it and wham it and wham it on this tree stump.

32:50.800 --> 32:55.100
That a tremendous amount of anger, he didn't fit in with other people.

32:55.460 --> 33:00.760
He wanted to be somewhere else, so he wrote about something that was like nothing he had experienced.

33:01.560 --> 33:04.580
It's hard not to psychoanalyze a guy like that, right?

33:04.920 --> 33:09.440
And see the barbarian chopping the heads off, and see him out there whamming the tree stump.

33:10.120 --> 33:10.920
You really can.

33:10.920 --> 33:20.240
In other words too, you think that perhaps his theory of the, what, the ancient heroes of the past sort of reliving,

33:20.880 --> 33:27.080
or their force, their power, whatever you want to call it, their heroic action, sort of living in modern men,

33:27.920 --> 33:34.760
he sort of saw himself as an ancestor, or what, a remnant of that kind of ancient hero?

33:35.180 --> 33:39.420
I descend that the last one left, the one who didn't, didn't...

33:39.420 --> 33:40.180
The last count.

33:40.440 --> 33:42.920
Yes, he saw himself as the last count just about.

33:43.580 --> 33:46.120
Well, he didn't, he wouldn't go so far as to believe in reincarnation, would he?

33:46.280 --> 33:47.740
Sometimes it almost sounds like it.

33:47.760 --> 33:50.960
I'm not that good with it, but I really doubt that he actually believed it.

33:52.300 --> 33:55.940
I remember, and I forget, I think the character's name was James Allison,

33:56.540 --> 33:58.600
a Valley of the Worm, I think, in one of his works.

34:00.300 --> 34:06.840
He is, I think he's on the point of dying as James Allison character is, and he's like Howard, he's a remnant.

34:06.840 --> 34:11.100
He's a powerful individual, a great hero, he doesn't fit, but he's in the modern world.

34:12.460 --> 34:18.080
And he recalls the heroes from the Dragon Slayers, the Worm Slayers from the past,

34:18.800 --> 34:25.620
all the way back to an original, I think, who was called Njord, who killed a huge worm-like creature,

34:25.840 --> 34:34.220
back in prehistory, and Allison remembers all the incarnations that this hero's force had passed through to get to James Allison.

34:34.220 --> 34:38.700
Which makes you wonder how much H. Ryder Haggard was in his library.

34:39.340 --> 34:43.760
Was there any? That sounds a lot like H. Ryder Haggard's heroes.

34:50.880 --> 34:56.540
There again, I don't think, I don't know how seriously you can take anything that Howard said he believed,

34:56.720 --> 35:03.060
because he was constantly trying to create an image of himself and project that to other people.

35:03.060 --> 35:06.520
So I don't think we can say he did believe in reincarnation or he didn't.

35:06.520 --> 35:09.020
If he said outright that he did, it doesn't mean that he did.

35:12.900 --> 35:17.860
He was interested too in all kinds of sports, wasn't he? Boxing, football, manly sports?

35:18.120 --> 35:25.000
He did not like football, didn't like any kind of team sports. He liked boxing, he liked the idea of fencing.

35:25.560 --> 35:29.340
The sports he was interested in, well he did go to football games some,

35:29.340 --> 35:35.160
but from his experience with the basketball team when he was a young boy, he was not good at team sports,

35:35.280 --> 35:40.960
he couldn't cooperate with other people, and he saw the truly admirable sports to be the one on one.

35:41.980 --> 35:44.560
He's been a good hockey player, where he's whacked people over the pail.

35:45.460 --> 35:51.360
What's he a good boxer, do you know? I mean, you said he took care of himself, he was very interested in physical fitness.

35:52.060 --> 35:57.620
And is there a picture of him in the last cal, striking the hose with the fists up?

35:58.320 --> 36:02.240
But I don't know of any actual fights that he ever got into.

36:02.400 --> 36:07.580
No, I don't believe so. To answer your other question, he had three H. Ryder Haverd books in his library.

36:08.700 --> 36:10.540
Alan Quatermain, is that the title? Yeah.

36:10.700 --> 36:12.580
Ancient Alan and People of the Rest.

36:13.220 --> 36:14.660
That's a good surprise.

36:17.360 --> 36:26.140
Dr. Loughlin, can you tell us something about the discovery of the Howard manuscripts and the controversies and the problems that have come up in that area?

36:26.600 --> 36:28.300
Yes, a little bit of it.

