And I believe he was trying... Mr. de Camp was trying to sell this story to Don Woham, or he was...

37:14.800 --> 37:17.120
For some reason he was discussing it with Don Woham.

37:17.120 --> 37:27.040
And Woham said, well, I understand that Oscar J. Friend has a whole box of unpublished Howard manuscripts, which you'd be interested in those.

37:27.700 --> 37:31.440
And Mr. de Camp just came unglued. Yes, I'm interested in the very next day.

37:31.540 --> 37:37.660
He went rushing over to Oscar Friends and asked for the box. I don't know if he had to pay for them.

37:38.060 --> 37:44.440
Oscar J. Friend was a literary agent associated with Otis Klein literary agency that Robert Howard used.

37:44.440 --> 37:50.680
And he still had this box of things. It was in... That was in November of 1950.

37:51.280 --> 37:54.700
So actually Mr. de Camp was the one who found the first hoard of manuscripts.

37:56.160 --> 38:03.040
And then a little later, it was either Friends or Klein's daughter inherited that literary agency.

38:03.340 --> 38:06.720
And she did not want to handle Howard manuscripts. She didn't like the stuff.

38:07.100 --> 38:09.540
And so she told that a camp said, have to find someone else.

38:09.540 --> 38:16.100
And Mrs. de Camp wanted to be the literary executor. But Mr. de Camp didn't think this would be fair.

38:16.680 --> 38:19.780
You see, because they had the manuscripts, didn't mean they had the copyright.

38:20.040 --> 38:26.300
The copyright was still owned by the Kirk and Dolls because Dr. Howard had left the Kirk and Dolls everything,

38:26.780 --> 38:29.580
which included the rights to his son's copyright.

38:30.260 --> 38:32.160
So they were having a deal with the Kirk and Dolls.

38:32.280 --> 38:36.640
And Mr. de Camp thought it might be a little bit fair for his own life to be the literary executor.

38:36.640 --> 38:41.520
So he called Glen Lord. He had never met him. I don't believe they had corresponded.

38:41.560 --> 38:47.480
He was just a very active fan. And he asked Glen Lord to do it, which of course they agreed to do.

38:48.100 --> 38:55.520
And he took his job very seriously. And he traced down a second box of unpublished manuscripts in California.

38:56.220 --> 39:03.280
When Robert died, his father seemed to find it very painful to have things of Roberts around the house.

39:03.280 --> 39:10.040
So he gave them away. He gave away baby pictures. Very nice studio portrait baby pictures.

39:10.460 --> 39:16.540
He gave away all of his manuscripts. And he gave one box, I believe, was to Clark Ashton Smith.

39:16.960 --> 39:21.260
It was someone in California, a writer with whom Howard had cordial correspondence.

39:21.880 --> 39:27.000
And he felt very grateful to the people who had had cordial relations with Robert because he had so few friends.

39:27.000 --> 39:30.460
So his father gave all of them presents, mementos of Robert.

39:31.080 --> 39:36.700
And whoever this writer was, it may have been Smith, loaned the box of manuscript to a fan.

39:38.860 --> 39:41.420
And the fan never returned them. He couldn't get them back.

39:42.020 --> 39:48.520
And then in the meantime, Clark Ashton Smith or whatever the writer was, and the fan both died.

39:49.360 --> 39:55.160
And the box of manuscripts is in some of the things that the family goes through.

39:55.160 --> 39:59.880
And they don't know what they are or what to do with them. So they're just stuffed off somewhere in the box and forgotten about.

40:00.980 --> 40:04.980
And then Lord managed to trace that down. Sort of a little detective hunt.

40:05.140 --> 40:08.900
But he had to go on to find them. And he did find that in 1965.

40:09.840 --> 40:14.960
And he had to buy them from, you know, buy the physical manuscripts. He didn't have to buy the copyright.

40:15.360 --> 40:19.980
But he had to buy them from whoever had them at the time. And that was far none as close some.

40:20.100 --> 40:22.240
I understand it was sizable in 1965.

40:24.440 --> 40:29.200
Do you think we have all of Howard manuscripts today? Or might there still be some around?

40:29.320 --> 40:35.640
There's always rumors that there are some around. You know, it was when Dr. Howard gave the library to Howard Payne,

40:35.680 --> 40:42.200
there were rumors that he also gave the manuscripts. We do know that he gave copies of the pulp magazines that Howard had been published in.

40:42.640 --> 40:49.180
And at some time, Dr. Howard came and retrieved the magazines. He told his friends that the students were reading them to pieces.

40:49.180 --> 40:56.940
And that's why he came to get them. The story around Howard Payne is that the librarian thought that the ladies on the covers of weird tales

40:56.940 --> 41:00.460
and the pulp magazines were not quite far-belonged at a Baptist university.

41:00.740 --> 41:03.900
So she hid them in the basement of Old Main, which is the building right now.

41:04.260 --> 41:08.340
And he got rather damp down there than were ruining. So that's why the father got them.

41:08.700 --> 41:12.400
The story, there's a story that T. R. Havens, who was a historian here.

41:13.240 --> 41:17.900
And the librarian, another librarian, well, she was not a librarian. She was a secretary or something.

41:17.900 --> 41:23.760
Lena Vincent, Tuit Vincent's sister, Tuit Vincent was a close friend of Howard, who he lives in Austin now.

41:24.160 --> 41:31.200
That Lena Vincent and T. R. Havens realized that this librarian was going to throw out a bunch of this junk that she thought was un-Christian.

41:31.720 --> 41:37.760
So they put it in the back seat of their car and someone said the whole back seat was full and it included manuscripts.

41:38.280 --> 41:48.120
And people have even, it might have been, in large, someone actually saw one of the manuscripts in Dr. Haven's desk here about 15 years ago.

41:48.340 --> 41:52.940
And he had a type script that he pulled out and showed. But Dr. Havens is now dead.

41:53.640 --> 41:59.180
His widow is now dead. And if there was anything there, we'll probably never hear from him.

42:00.260 --> 42:06.920
I think also an extension of that kind of confusion is the, what happens today if you walk into a bookstore and go to the fantasy section,

42:06.920 --> 42:12.140
you'll find at least three publishing houses publishing the Howard material.

42:12.280 --> 42:17.600
I think it's Berkeley and Bantam and Ace, I believe it is. Or is Lancer a fourth one?

42:18.040 --> 42:24.300
Lancer has gone out of business. Now that's an interesting story too. That's part of the controversy of the publication of what happened.

42:24.620 --> 42:28.920
And part of the zebra business is also, it's still with Lancer.

42:28.920 --> 42:33.580
Because Zacharias or whatever his name is was associated with both of them.

42:34.460 --> 42:40.340
The Lancer books were authorized. They were paid a certain amount for them. Nothing exorbitant.

42:40.840 --> 42:47.480
When Lancer went out of business, I believe it was Mr. Zacharias, took some of the things to zebra books.

42:49.760 --> 42:54.920
Then Lancer sold to someone who was buying up bankrupt companies.

42:55.660 --> 43:04.480
And they were claiming a law under which a company that does not go bankrupt but reorganizes does not lose the copyrights.

43:05.140 --> 43:11.400
In the contracts they had, they had a bankruptcy cause. And if the publisher went bankrupt, they got back the copyrights.

43:11.400 --> 43:14.460
But they were in court for years on that.

43:14.460 --> 43:20.920
And in the meantime, Glen Lord and some others sold the rights to Berkeley.

43:21.580 --> 43:25.180
For what Mr. DeCamp thought was a pittance or something like that, I understand.

43:25.880 --> 43:32.220
But sure enough, they lost the suit. And Lancer was allowed to claim.

43:32.880 --> 43:34.180
You should have taken out the hook.

43:38.100 --> 43:42.820
Glen Lord and some of the Conan group felt certain that they would win the lawsuit with Lancer.

43:42.820 --> 43:47.920
So they went ahead and sold the rights to the Conan material to Berkeley Books.

43:48.120 --> 43:50.460
And Berkeley started producing the books, publishing them.

43:50.940 --> 43:55.160
But in the meantime, they lost the lawsuit. Lancer won.

43:55.360 --> 43:58.480
They were allowed to claim that it was a reorganization, not a bankruptcy.

43:59.180 --> 44:02.140
So the copyrights did not return for the publishing rights.

44:03.340 --> 44:09.340
And the reorganizer, the person who had actually bought Lancer out, had sold the rights to Ace Books.

44:09.340 --> 44:15.860
And Ace had already produced them all, that 12 numerical series of Conan books.

44:15.980 --> 44:20.820
They were all ready to go. And when this decision was reached in, I think, March of 77,

44:22.460 --> 44:24.480
they rushed them to the market immediately.

44:24.940 --> 44:27.320
And the writers and the Conan people didn't get any money.

44:27.540 --> 44:31.160
And they actually called it a kind of piracy.

44:31.780 --> 44:33.320
But they settled that out.

44:33.500 --> 44:36.160
Of course, they didn't engage a lawyer, author, Lieberman,

44:36.160 --> 44:39.420
who had them organize what he called Conan properties,

44:39.900 --> 44:43.520
which has made Conan a registered trademark so that not anybody can use it.

44:43.980 --> 44:46.680
And I don't know exactly who all the members of Conan properties are,

44:46.700 --> 44:50.720
but it includes DeKamp and Glen Lard and Arthur Lieberman the lawyer.

44:51.340 --> 44:54.600
And I want to say Kirby McCauley, who was the literary agent.

44:55.600 --> 44:59.160
And there are two others. I believe there are six people, so people who are members of that.

45:00.960 --> 45:03.620
Is there an authorized publisher at the present time?

45:04.840 --> 45:07.220
Bantam is doing the new pastiches.

45:07.880 --> 45:11.760
And so far as I know, Ace is doing all of the older things.

45:12.800 --> 45:14.880
But I don't know about an authorized publisher.

45:15.220 --> 45:17.020
Is this by agreement among themselves?

45:17.400 --> 45:20.700
Like Bantam does the pastiches, you say?

45:21.680 --> 45:23.680
Just the pastiches? Dr. Crater, is that correct?

45:24.160 --> 45:29.940
Well, not entirely, because they've done the Solomon King books and some of the others.

45:29.940 --> 45:36.880
But I know that recently Ace has been issuing the Conan originals by Howard,

45:37.100 --> 45:41.520
that is the reprints of the Conan series are being done by Ace, apparently.

45:41.780 --> 45:44.240
I don't believe anything is done by agreement among themselves.

45:44.380 --> 45:47.500
There's tremendous lawsuits that go on over the whole thing.

45:48.200 --> 45:52.200
I'm certain Conan properties had to settle with Ace about what they could do.

45:53.280 --> 45:56.740
Now the writers of the pastiches can deal with the publisher directly,

45:56.740 --> 46:02.740
but a portion of anything they do that is a Conan pastiche has to be paid into Conan properties.

46:03.500 --> 46:07.420
And Glen Lorde's literary agent gets 5% off the top of that.

46:07.740 --> 46:10.340
Now he was not always a literary agent, Kirby McCauley was,

46:10.820 --> 46:14.660
but Glen Lorde, I believe now is the one who gets the 5%.

46:14.660 --> 46:19.060
In other words, a publishing house can contract with any author to do a Conan book,

46:19.920 --> 46:23.260
as long as it's a pastiche and a certain percentage is given to the estate.

46:23.260 --> 46:28.780
Well, the Conan properties has to agree to let you use that name.

46:29.620 --> 46:31.960
And they don't agree to let just anybody use it.

46:32.500 --> 46:37.840
And if they agree to let you use the name, a certain percentage of your profits has to be paid to them.

46:39.080 --> 46:41.380
How many authors are doing pastiches or have none?

46:42.120 --> 46:48.520
We don't know of Andy Offit, Paul Anderson, Al Sprave Camp, Len Carter,

46:49.140 --> 46:52.640
DeKamp and Carter in collaboration, Bjorn Nyberg,

46:53.480 --> 46:55.420
and DeKamp in collaboration.

46:56.480 --> 46:57.860
Who have we left out?

47:01.360 --> 47:06.720
Now, as we said, I think Carl Edward Wagner was planning to do one.

47:07.260 --> 47:08.400
He did one, didn't he?

47:08.480 --> 47:12.280
He did one, and planning to a second, that one never appeared.

47:12.420 --> 47:13.820
But I believe he did do one.

47:14.000 --> 47:15.100
So that would be another one.

47:15.720 --> 47:18.380
He did one in a band-aum, series of six.

47:19.160 --> 47:20.980
What about those kinds that you just meant?

